{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-10011/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-10011"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["1:00:11"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["medium shot"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["low"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["mobile, pan, tilt"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["single shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A woman speaks to another woman."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-10011/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-10011","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-10011/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-10011"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-10011/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-10011/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-10011/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-10011/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-10011/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-10011/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-10011/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-10011/canvas/1/bcf69793-6b45-42fd-86d5-fb1b6b3dfea9","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-30T17:09:16.210Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Ethan Warren, applying George Toles’s work on PTA’s early films to <em>Phantom Thread</em>, sees Alma’s presence in Reynolds’s life as a challenge to the kind of patriarchal order that the tailor represents: “As with many of Toles’s arguments on the female presence in Anderson’s work, he predicts with eerie prescience the themes and techniques of <em>Phantom Thread</em>. Alma represents an ideal example of Toles’s ‘emergence of the irrational,’ a presence ‘meant to disrupt or dissolve a chain of causality associated with the patriarchal order—a masculine mode of logic based on gaining or preserving control’” (Warren, <em>The Cinema of Paul Thomas Anderson</em>, 110).</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-10011/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:461.3940653669724,115.84145642201838,411.73451834862396,529.4595756880734"}}}]}]}]}